Using GNU Stow is exactly what the "big boys" do. It uses symlinks to make the system think your config is in the home directory, while the actual file lives safely in a version-controlled folder.

The "Golden Rule" Pattern
To solve your concern about apps "screwing up" your file, you need to adopt the Boilerplate + Local pattern. Stop putting everything in ~/.bashrc.

The Git-Managed File (~/.bashrc): This contains only your core logic and "sources" other files.

The Local File (~/.bashrc.local): This file is ignored by Git. If an app (like an installer) wants to inject code, or if you have machine-specific settings (like a work email or specific GPU drivers), it goes here.

How to Set It Up (Pay Attention)
1. The Directory Structure
Create a dotfiles folder. Inside, mimic your home directory structure:

Plaintext
~/dotfiles/
└── bash/
    ├── .bashrc
    ├── .bash_aliases
    └── .bash_functions
2. The "Shielded" .bashrc
Modify your managed .bashrc to look for a local file at the very end. This way, if an installer appends something to ~/.bashrc, you’ll see it in your Git diff and can move it to the .local file manually.

Bash
