We’re going to write a simple shell script inside your ~/dotfiles directory. This script handles the heavy lifting: installing the essentials, cloning your repo (if it’s not already there), and letting Stow do its job.

The "Zero-to-Hero" Bootstrap Script
Create a file named install.sh in your ~/dotfiles folder:

Bash
#!/bin/bash

# Define the packages you actually need to function
PACKAGES=(
    "stow"
    "starship"
    "zoxide"
    "fzf"
    "git"
)

echo "--- Starting Bootstrap ---"

# 1. Install missing packages (Arch specific)
# Using 'pacman -Qi' to check if already installed so we don't waste time
for pkg in "${PACKAGES[@]}"; do
    if ! pacman -Qi "$pkg" &> /dev/null; then
        echo "Installing $pkg..."
        sudo pacman -S --noconfirm "$pkg"
    fi
done

# 2. Navigate to dotfiles directory
DOTFILES_DIR=$(cd "$(dirname "${BASH_SOURCE[0]}")" && pwd)
cd "$DOTFILES_DIR"

# 3. Stow the configurations
# This creates the symlinks for bash. Add other folders as you grow.
echo "Stowing configurations..."
stow bash

# 4. Create the local bypass file if it doesn't exist
# This prevents your .bashrc from crying when it looks for it
if [ ! -f ~/.bashrc.local ]; then
    touch ~/.bashrc.local
    echo "# Machine-specific overrides go here" > ~/.bashrc.local
fi

echo "--- Done. Restart your shell and try not to break it. ---"
How to Use This (Pay Attention)
Make it executable: chmod +x ~/dotfiles/install.sh

Run it: ./install.sh

The Result: Your ~/.bashrc is now a symlink, your tools are installed, and your .bashrc.local is ready for whatever weird machine-specific junk you need.

