The "Git-Push" Deployment
The most elegant way to handle this is a Git Hook. Specifically, a post-receive hook on your server.

1. On the Server: Create a Bare Repo
Instead of a normal folder, you create a "bare" repository that acts as the target for your laptop’s git push.

Bash
mkdir -p ~/repos/dotfiles.git
cd ~/repos/dotfiles.git
git init --bare
2. On the Server: The Hook (The "Magic")
Create a file at ~/repos/dotfiles.git/hooks/post-receive and make it executable (chmod +x). This script triggers every time you push code to the server.

Bash
#!/bin/bash
# Define where the actual files should live
TARGET="/home/$USER/dotfiles"
GIT_DIR="/home/$USER/repos/dotfiles.git"

# 1. Checkout the files into the target folder
git --work-tree=$TARGET --git-dir=$GIT_DIR checkout -f

# 2. Run your bootstrap script to ensure Stow and tools are updated
bash $TARGET/install.sh
3. On Your Laptop: Add the Remote
Tell your local dotfiles repo that your server exists:

Bash
git remote add server user@your-server-ip:repos/dotfiles.git
The Workflow (Pay Attention)
You edit a file on your laptop.

You run git commit -am "Update aliases".

You run git push server main.

The result: The server receives the code, checks it out into ~/dotfiles, and automatically runs your install.sh script to update the symlinks. Your server is now a perfect clone of your local environment without you ever having to manually touch it.

Why This is the "Adult" Way to Do It
Atomicity: Your changes happen all at once.

Hands-off: You don't have to remember to "update" your server; the push is the update.

Versatility: You can have multiple remotes (e.g., git push github and git push homelab).

