Think of direnv as a ghost that lives in your shell and silently switches your environment variables based on which folder you’re standing in. It’s the "Adult" way to handle things like API keys, Python virtual environments, or custom PATHs without cluttering your global ~/.bashrc.

The "Problem" It Solves
