Yes, subdirectories have access. By default, direnv looks "up" the directory tree. If you are in ~/projects/app/src, and your .envrc is in ~/projects/app/, direnv will find it and load it.

This is beautiful because you can define your environment at the root of a project, and every deep-nested folder you cd into will inherit those variables. The moment you cd out of the project root's hierarchy, the variables are nuked from your environment.

2. The "Global but Not Global" AWS Problem
For things like AWS keys or GitHub tokens that you use across many projects, you have three choices, ranked from "Amateur" to "Professional":

Option A: The Lazy Way (Standard ~/.aws/credentials)
AWS (and many other tools) already has a standard way to handle this. You run aws configure, and it saves your keys in ~/.aws/credentials.

The Good: Most tools look here automatically.

The Bad: It's another "secret" file you have to remember to back up (and NOT put in your dotfiles).

Option B: The direnv "Source" Pattern (The Smart Way)
If you want to use direnv for these, create a central "Secrets" folder that is strictly excluded from your Git repo (e.g., ~/.local/secrets/).
Inside your project's .envrc, you can do this:

Bash
# ~/projects/my-app/.envrc
source_env ~/.local/secrets/aws.envrc
export PROJECT_SPECIFIC_VAR="whatever"
This allows you to maintain one central file for AWS keys while only "activating" them for specific projects.

Option C: The 1Password/Bitwarden CLI (The "I Value My Career" Way)
This is what we actually do in the industry. You store your secrets in a password manager. Your .envrc then looks like this:

Bash
# This fetches the secret from your vault on the fly
export AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID="$(op read op://vault/aws/access_key)"
No secrets on disk. No secrets in Git. Just pure, encrypted bliss.

3. How to Transfer Them (The "Don't Use Slack" Rule)
Whatever you do, never email your keys, put them in a private Git repo, or send them over Discord/Slack.

For Personal Use: Use a specialized tool like Tailscale Send, Wormhole, or just sync your password manager (Bitwarden/1Password) vault across your machines.

For Servers: Use a "Secret Store" or just manually copy the file once over a secure SSH connection (scp).

The Pattern Summary
Secret Type	Storage Location	Loading Method
Project Specific	project/.envrc	direnv (Auto)
Global/AWS	~/.aws/credentials	Native Tooling
Cross-Project	~/.local/secrets/	source_env in .envrc
